// create function init() which is a specialized method in the golang which runs only at the very //first time and only once
func init() {
	//client option for connecting with mongodb
	clientOption := options.Client().ApplyURI(connectionString)

	//connect to mongodb using mongo.Connect() with context and clientOption and returns client or error, so we use comma ok syntax
	client, err := mongo.Connect(context.TODO(), clientOption)

	//goto pkg.go.dev - context package
	/*Package context defines the Context type, which carries deadlines, cancellation signals, and other request-scoped values across API boundaries and between processes. which means whenever you are making a call to some machine which is outside of your machine (ie) db is usually outside and in this case specially it is on to some web server then we need to provide a context that for how long we can make a request and what happens when the request goes off and if the connection is still active,there should be a context on which we can work.
	If we see types of context, we have background, todo
	1.background -  if anything happens in the background it returns a non nil empty context, it is never cancelled and has no values and has no deadline so if you want something that keeps on happening in the background just go ahead and use the context.background
	2. todo - we use the context.todo when it is unclear which context to use, so in this case if you have no idea what context to use in all those places you can use the todo */
/*In most of the methods when we contact to the mongodb to insert value or get value in that case
majority you will be using the context.background, but in majority of the cases where you have no idea we can use context.todo */

	//check for error
	if err != nil {
		log.Fatal(err) //we can use panic also
	}
	fmt.Println("MongoDB connection success")

	//we don't want just a database connection, we want to create a database, a column name
	//we need a simple reference of that so that i can use them anywhere using collection variable
	collection = client.Database(dbName).Collection(colName)

	//collection instance
	fmt.Println("Collection instance is ready")
}


