Concurrency and goroutines in golang
     So far whatever the projects we have built up, even the minifolders, while loop, for loop they are complete in itself, so the project actually work it does the job what it is intended to   do. Now the goal is not to just complete the stuff, the goal is to understand the things, why they are happening, what they are actually doing 
    First we're going to talk about concurrency and parallelism. For example, consider you're eating your food and there is a notification in your phone which is an instagram notification
and you're also feeling hot so you want to turn on the air conditioner. Now you can do it through
concurrency or you can do it in parallelism also.
    So what is concurrency and how you do it, so you are eating food, so you don't check
your phone while eating the food, so that means you are not giving even the parallelism or the concurrency, you just do one task at a time, you just eat the food you don't check the mobile phone and you also don't turn on the air condition because that's what you do at one time.
    But on the other hand there is a scenario where you are eating the food, so the notification come in, you left the plate you picked up the phone you check the notification, you put down the phone down, then you turn on the ac you put down the remote, you look back on instagram you put the phone down, then you start again eating your food, now this is known as concurrency. You are
allowing yourself to get involved into doing multiple tasks, but you are not doing them at the same time, you are kind of doing them at the same time but not exactly, you are putting down your phone, then you are picking up the plate to eat the food and then you're putting down the plate and then you are using the remote to turn on the ac, now this is exactly what is being
represented as concurrency, you are allowed to do multiple tasks but your task is going to
be done at one given time 
      Parallelism is you are eating your food with one spoon you put up the food in your mouth, you're checking the instagram, you're turning on the ac and getting back onto your food
this is parallelism. You're doing all the things at the one task. This is difference between concurrency and parallelism
     goroutines is the way how you achieve this parallelism, now goroutines often are being compared with the threads as well, but there are just two major differences up here. 
     The threads are managed by os on the other hand, the goroutines are managed by the
go runtime. So go runtime can actually fire up more threads without even getting permission from os, of course os is responsible for allotting your threads but in this the more control is actually in the go runtime and that is the reason why this language is more popular in the
cloud, because in the cloud environment we have no shortage of these threads and we can take advantage of all of them
    In the thread there is a fixed stack being used of 1mb, surely we can refer to other memories to read and write and can increase that, but by default the threads are 1 mb that is like the minimum of having a thread. On the goroutine the threads are of just 2 kb, so you can imagine just in a limited amount of memory how many threads you can fire up and each thread can be responsible for bringing up more data. Maybe you are hitting up 12 different apis and you can fire up each thread to bring up data from each of those apis so that will be done so much faster

