     In previous program we discussed if we have multiple goroutines, these go routines can actually access to a single memory, all of this go routine are struggling to to write this memory and we solve that issue by using the mutex. But sometimes it is not feasible that you declare a
global variable or you use database to write a value, your go routine just go up in the internet  do some operation pick some values add that entry into the database and then your go routines start another
      First go routine has no idea about next go routine, you can say that this waitgroup is there to make it aware, but wait group is just a management here, waitgroup doesn't tell that there is another goroutine waiting for it, it says nothing about it, it will just do your job send me a
done signal and i'll take care of the rest and this actually brings us the concept of channels


Why Channels?
      Channels are a way in which your multiple go routines can actually talk to each other, they will still not be aware of what's happening inside that or what long it's going to take another go
routine to finish of the job, but maybe you are waiting for just some signal or just some information from another go routine and you don't need to go come back and finish all of that and you can do it on the go while the thread has not completed the execution 


